entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued April 19 at 7:57PM CDT by NWS Duluth MN
entry.summary:
At 753 PM CDT, a line of moderate to heavy snow showers were along a line extending from near Fond Du Lac Band Cloquet Area to near Moose Lake State Park to 9 miles northeast of McGrath, and moving southeast at 30 mph towards the Interstate 35 corridor in east- central Minnesota. Very little accumlating snow is expected with this line of snow showers.
Visibilities of 1/2 mile or less and wind gusts up to 30 mph have been observed with this line of moderate to heavy snow showers.
These moderate to heavy snow showers will be near... Carlton, Willow River, Wrenshall, Thomson, Nemadji, Moose Lake State Park, and Jay Cooke State Park around 800 PM CDT. Rutledge around 805 PM CDT. Holyoke, Bruno, and Banning State Park around 810 PM CDT.
Other locations impacted by these moderate to heavy snow showers include Finlayson, Arthyde, Pleasant Valley, Sturgeon Lake, Scotts Corner, Duquette, Nickerson, Denham, and Kerrick.
Be prepared for changing visibility and road conditions. Reduce your speed and allow more space between you and the vehicle in front of you.

This rainfall will only become more widespread as we go through the day Saturday and especially Saturday Night. Look for widespread rainfall amounts of near one to three inches with isolated higher amounts possible. The rainfall should quickly exit the Four State Region from west to east during the day Sunday.
While rainfall rates will likely not be excessive enough to result in widespread flash flooding, poor drainage and flood prone areas will be susceptible to flooding. The greater impacts will likely come from already swollen bayous, lakes and rivers which remain high from previous rainfall. This forecast rainfall will likely result in either a slow down to recent falling trends or additional rises on most all area waterways that will continue into next week.

The Arizona Department of Environmental Quality (ADEQ) has issued an Ozone High Pollution Advisory for the Phoenix Metro Area Saturday through Sunday.
This means that forecast weather conditions combined with existing ozone levels are expected to result in local maximum 8-hour ozone concentrations that pose a health risk. Adverse health effects increase as air quality deteriorates.
Ozone is an air contaminant which can cause breathing difficulties for children, older adults, as well as persons with respiratory problems. A decrease in physical activity is recommended.
You are urged to car pool, telecommute or use mass transit. The use of gasoline-powered equipment should be reduced or done late in the day.
